      • getArgumentTypes

        public ArgumentTypes[] getArgumentTypes()
        Description copied from interface: ICommand
        Gets the argument types for the command parameters. If an argument is optional, use ArgumentTypes.optional(). If your command takes special arguments that cannot be processed by this library, then make sure to include ArgumentTypes.CUSTOM at the end of this array. If the command does not take any arguments, this method can return null.

        NOTE: ArgumentTypes.CUSTOM is not used for custom arguments. If you want your command to take a special/custom argument, then use ArgumentTypes.STRING, and parse the argument yourself in ICommand.execute(MessageReceivedEvent, CommandRegistry, String, Object...).

        NOTE: If you use ArgumentTypes.CUSTOM, your command will not show any arguments on the default help command unless it extends ManuallyProcessedCommand.

        NOTE: Array and optional types must be the last arguments in the arguments array. Each command may only have one optional argument. Command may not have both array and optional arguments.
        Specified by:
        getArgumentTypes in interface ICommand
        Returns:
        the argument types, or null.

      • getArgumentTypesString

        public abstract java.lang.String[] getArgumentTypesString()
        Gets the argument types for the command parameters. The best way to implement this method is to use ArgumentTypes.toString(), as most of your arguments should already exist in the ArgumentTypes class.
        Returns:
        a string array of the argument types for this command.
